@Node FreePTModule

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  FreePTModule(#@{b}Module@{ub}.w)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Frees a module object earlyer initialized
  with LoadPTModule().

  @{b}Module@{ub}
  The module to free.
@EndNode


@Node GetPTModulePos

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  @{b}Result@{ub}.b = GetPTModulePos()

    @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
  Read the song position from the currently
  played module.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
  The currently song position, which range
  from 0 to 127.
@EndNode


@Node GetPTModuleRow

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  @{b}Result@{ub}.b = GetPTModuleRow()

    @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
  Read the row number from the currently
  played module.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
  The actual row, range from 0 to 63.
@EndNode


@Node InitPTModule

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  @{b}Result@{ub}.l = InitPTModule(@{b}Modules@{ub}.l)

    @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
  This is the initroutine and it must always be called
  befor any other PTModule functions.

  Note:
  ====
  The new Audio Lib serve both PTModule Lib and Sound
  Lib with the allocation/freeing functions of audio
  channels.  The little drawback is that InitAudio()
  must always be called before InitPTModule().

  @{b}Modules@{ub}
  The max module objects wanted.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
  If this is TRUE the PTModule environment is correctly
  initialized but if it's instead FALSE no other
  function should be called.
@EndNode


@Node LoadPTModule

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  @{b}Result@{ub}.l = LoadPTModule(#@{b}Module@{ub}.w,@{b}FileName@{ub}$)

    @{b}FUNCTION@{ub}
  Use this function to load a module from disk,
  it must be the 31 samples 64 pattern type of
  ProTracker module.

  The module object must be free else the old
  stuff will be gone.

  @{b}Module@{ub}
  The module object to initialize.

  @{b}FileName@{ub}
  An ordinary path to the module.

  @{b}Result@{ub}
  If TRUE the module have been correctly
  loaded.
@EndNode


@Node PausePTModule

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  PausePTModule()

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Call this statement to have the currently
  played module paused.

  The paused module could be resumed later
  on even if one or more modules have been
  played, and paused too, in between.
@EndNode


@Node PlayPTModule

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  PlayPTModule(#@{b}Module@{ub}.w)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Use this statement to start to play
  an module.

  The currently played module will be
  stoped automaticly.

  @{b}Module@{ub}
  The module to play.
@EndNode


@Node ResumePTModule

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  ResumePTModule(#@{b}Module@{ub}.w)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Use this statement to resume any paused module,
  not just the currently played module that is
  paused, at any time

  The currently played module will be
  stoped automaticly.

  @{b}Module@{ub}
  The module to resume.
@EndNode


@Node SetPTModulePos

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  SetPTModulePos(@{b}Pos@{ub}.b)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  To set a new song position for the currently
  played module then call this statement.

  @{b}Pos@{ub}
  The new song position.
@EndNode


@Node SetPTModuleRow

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  SetPTModuleRow(@{b}Row@{ub}.b)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  To set a new row number for the currently
  played module then call this statement.

  @{b}Row@{ub}
  The new row number to set, must
  be in between 0 to 63.
@EndNode


@Node SetPTModuleSpeed

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  SetPTModuleSpeed(@{b}Speed@{ub}.b)

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  This statement set a new speed value for
  the currently played module.

  @{b}Speed@{ub}
  The new speed, could be somewhere in
  between 1 and 32.

  As the value gets lower the module
  will go faster.
@EndNode


@Node StopPTModule

    @{b}SYNTAX@{ub}
  StopPTModule()

    @{b}STATEMENT@{ub}
  Use this statement to stop the
  currently played module.
@EndNode

